Date: 0/0/1898
Source: Merriam-Webster Third International
Author:
Vol / Page: 2031
Edition:
Quote: <i> Squat&#769;.ter </i>(-t&etilde.r),<i> n. [Add.] 3 </i>. The owner or occupant of a sheep run; a sheep farmer. In Australia the word had at first the sense of a settler without title; but its use was gradually extended to persons who occupied crown land for sheep raising under a lease or a license, and afterwards to those also who held their sheep runs as freehold. Finally the word became the common name for a sheep farmer, whether occupying leasehold or freehold property. It is, however, giving way to the newer term <i> pastoralist </i>.
Notes:
